{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:54:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:54:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14377"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14377"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.44,0.01,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7072"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7072"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94849"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"737"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4506"},{"type":"tags","id":"4528"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46379"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the birthing suite with a six-hour history of vaginal fluid loss at 39 weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. This is her first pregnancy, which has been uncomplicated. Her antenatal records show a positive urine culture for \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus agalactiae\u003C/em\u003E (Group B Streptococcus) at the booking visit. She has been counselled earlier in pregnancy that she requires intravenous antibiotics in labour as the positive urine culture indicates heavy colonisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The fetal heart rate is 140/min. Sterile speculum examination confirms rupture of membranes with clear liquor. She expresses a preference for vaginal delivery but is hesitant about induction of labour.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer antibiotics and await spontaneous labour","Administer antibiotics and recommend immediate induction of labour","Expectant management with daily fetal monitoring","Expectant management for 24 hours then reassess","Recommend immediate caesarean section"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with ruptured membranes at term and known \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus agalactiae\u003C/em\u003E (Group B Streptococcus, GBS) colonisation from a positive urine culture. The presence of GBS in urine indicates heavy colonisation and is an indication for intrapartum antibiotic prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister antibiotics and recommend immediate induction of labour\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. This approach minimises the duration of ruptured membranes and reduces the risk of ascending infection and subsequent neonatal sepsis. The benefits of immediate induction outweigh the risks in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister antibiotics and await spontaneous labour\u003C/strong\u003E unnecessarily prolongs the duration of ruptured membranes, increasing the risk of neonatal GBS infection. While antibiotics are essential, they should be accompanied by active management to expedite delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management with daily fetal monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate in GBS-positive women with ruptured membranes at term. This approach increases the risk of neonatal infection without providing any significant benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management for 24 hours then reassess\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it unnecessarily delays delivery and increases infection risk. The presence of GBS colonisation makes immediate action necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend immediate caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as there are no obstetric contraindications to vaginal delivery. A caesarean section would expose the mother to unnecessary surgical risks without providing additional benefit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate induction of labour is recommended for term pregnancies with ruptured membranes and GBS colonisation to reduce the risk of neonatal sepsis.","GBS colonisation in urine during pregnancy is an indication for intrapartum antibiotic prophylaxis.","Expectant management in GBS-positive women with ruptured membranes increases the risk of neonatal GBS infection."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of perinatal infections. Melbourne: The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG); 2014. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf","The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Term prelabour rupture of membranes (Term PROM). 2010 [cited 2025 Sep 06]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Term-PROM.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94849"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14377"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94849"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-06T19:04:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-06T19:05:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7072"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta